And while the Pontiff is admitted to the Gemini with the doctors who yesterday emphasized that "it was not yet out of danger but that it is not at the moment in danger of life", the theme of the resignation of Bergoglio continues to be topical. "They all seem useless speculation." Now we are thinking about the health of the Holy Father, his recovery, his return to the Vatican: In an interview with Corriere della Sera, Cardinal Pietro Parolin, Vatican Secretary of State, returned three days ago from Burkina Faso. "Thank God, the news coming from the Gemelli are encouraging, is recovering. He has been sent office practices and this means that it proceeds well," says Parolin, who, on his possible visit, adds: "It is better that you stay protected and have fewer possible visits, so that you can rest and make the therapies to which you are subject more effective."
In these days false news and alarms have spread, we return to talk about "corvi" around the Vatican. "Sincertainly, I must say that I don't know if there are any maneuvers like this and I try, anyway, to stay out of it. On the other hand - Parolin observes -, I think it is quite normal that in these situations uncontrolled voices can be spread > or some comment is pronounced out of place: it is certainly not the first time that happens. But I do not think there is any particular movement, and so far I have not heard anything like that."
In the interview a call also to conflicts in Ukraine and the Middle East, Gaza, where Parolin warned against " unilateral provisions". "The authentic and just peace - the Vatican Secretary of State points out - is born from the involvement of all parties involved. Everyone must be involved and willing to negotiate to arrive at mutually accepted agreements. Otherwise peace will never be stable and lasting and the world will become a jungle in which conflicts will increase, with their terrible consequences of destruction and death." &nbsp;
<h2>Cardinal Dziwisz "resignation? From the cross do not descend"></h2>
"Our Pope is a wise man and will know what is right to do before the Lord. Meanwhile we pray and hope that you will soon return to lead the universal Church." Cardinal Stanislaw Dziwisz, > for more than forty years personal secretary of John Paul II and then archbishop emeritus of Kraków, responds to the Journal that interjects him on the days when the debate on the possible resignation of Francis at the threshold of Peter.
"Even John Paul II thought of his resignation > and spoke with Joseph Ratzinger (then Prefect of the former Holy Office, ed.)", Cardinal Dziwisz confessed. "He thought of it, of course, but also in the moments of greater suffering he repeated that from the cross do not descend. From the cross you don't come down, he always told me. And so he did, until the end." "I admire Pope Francis, I hope you will soon return to lead the universal church. He's a wise man and he'll know what to do in the face of God," Dziwisz says. "I can only say that we pray for the Holy Father so that he can soon return to drive Peter's boat." &nbsp;
